<p>Fr. Presler has served as rector of St. Peter's, Cambridge since 1991. During his rectorship the parish has reversed a membership decline, and revitalized its worship, community life, education programs and community outreach. Located in a low-income inner city neighborhood, St. Peter's is committed to serving its community through programs like Wordworks, a literacy ministry for recent immigrants, and Afterworks, a multicultural after-school ministry for children of inner-city families. </p>

<p>Following ordination as deacon in 1979, Fr. Presler served three years as curate and a year as interim rector at Christ Church in Hamilton, Mass. He then spent three years in Zimbabwe as rector of 12 congregations in the Bonda Church District, Diocese of Manicaland. While there he also served as secretary of the Commission on Ministry and chaired the Lay Ministry Training Team. He returned to Massachusetts in 1986 where he served as associate at Christ Church, Cambridge and later as interim rector at All Saints, Belmont and St. Chrysostom's, Quincy while pursuing doctoral studies at Harvard Divinity School and Episcopal Divinity School.</p>
 
<p>Fr. Presler has led retreats for parishes and religious orders and has served as chaplain to the Community of the Holy Transfiguration. In the Diocese of Massachusetts he chairs the Stewardship Commission and co-chairs the Volunteers for Mission Committee. He is active in community affairs through his work for several non-profit agencies including the YMCA, the Cambridge Community Foundation, and the Friends of the Cambridge Council on Aging. </p>

<p>At the national church level, Fr. Presler serves on the Nominating Committee for the Presiding Bishop, and the Standing Commission on World Mission. A four-time deputy to General Convention, Fr. Presler served as vice-chair of the House of Deputies World Mission Legislative Committee. He also was convenor of the Episcopal Council for Global Mission and directed the American Pilgrimage to the Centenary Bernard Mizeki Festival in Zimbabwe in 1995. </p>

<p>Before entering seminary, Fr. Presler was employed as a newspaper reporter and editor.</p>

